# PART I — DESIGN DOC

## Terminology
**"Init candidate"** = a starting candidate the run begins from (generated or supplied).
Deliberately NOT called a "seed" — that word is reserved for the RNG seed
(`random.Random(42)`) and overloading it would confuse humans and coding agents alike.
**"Baseline"** = the user-supplied reference model, flag `--baseline PATH` (rename of today's
`--baseline-py` — suffix dropped, name deliberately KEPT as "baseline": supplying a baseline vs
generated-only are **two different user intents** — a user passing this flag means "here's my
model, beat it," and the flag name should say so). The baseline has **zero privilege in search**
(M5): it enters as one init candidate alongside the N generated ones, and
"did we beat it" is answered by reading its lineage's outcome in the report. Generated-only
(cold-start) mode simply has no baseline.

## Purpose
**Generic cold-start.** SensorFlow is a generic platform: on a new problem there may be no
hand-tuned baseline at all. Multi-init makes the platform generate its own N starting init candidates
**from the contract alone**. An existing baseline (like this problem's hand-tuned tree) is
*optional supplied input* — just another init candidate with zero special status — not a structural
requirement. Breaking template lock-in at the root is a corollary benefit, not the purpose.

This is why M2 (the contract) is load-bearing: on a new problem, **the contract is all there
is** — no working parent exists anywhere in the system to copy from. The contract is the
platform's entire specification of the problem to the init generator.

**Relationship to novelty:** complementary. Multi-init diversifies the *starting* population;
`novelty` injects diversity *mid-search* with accumulated context. Both feed the same
protection + provenance machinery.

**Relationship to the negative-result deliverable:** each init candidate founds its own lineage, so the
run summary states per-architecture outcomes. "Did we beat the supplied model" is answered by
reading the supplied lineage's outcome — no privileged reference exists.

## Accepted risks (deliberately not defended against)
- **Broken init candidate (returns None / crashes):** dies at evaluation as a tagged dead-end;
  self-limiting (one failed try). No init-candidate validation built — v1 raises loudly, per primer.
- **Weak-but-valid init candidate:** dominated instantly; the grace period bounds the waste to the
  protection window (a bounded, deliberate fair-trial cost — same tradeoff already accepted for
  novelty lineages).

## Locked decisions

### M1 — Init candidates are GENERATED (not human-authored)
Alternative init candidates are produced by the LLM via a new **init-generation prompt** — a third prompt type:
generation from the task contract alone (not mutation of a parent, not reimagining of one).
Scalable and in the tool's spirit; inherits the candidate-contract crash surface, addressed by M2.

### M2 — Prerequisite: extend the contract summary (agent audits; two known gaps are the floor)
A contract summary exists today covering the **evaluator brief** and the **interface contract**
(`train_candidate(context, **kwargs)` + `model.pkl` convention). Two gaps are KNOWN and must be
added:
- **Data contract:** what `context` carries, data paths/CSVs, feature/label shape. Never
  documented because every candidate so far *inherited* working data-loading code from a parent;
  a generated init candidate is the first candidate written without one — uniquely exposed. Extract from
  the existing baseline's code.
- **Serialization constraints (the known killer):** codify the paid-for failures as rules:
  (1) classes must be module-level, NEVER inside functions (`<locals>` classes cannot be pickled
  — the `_Pipeline` crash); (2) prefer bare sklearn estimators the evaluator's size introspection
  handles. Packaging constraint, not architectural guidance — domain-free principle intact.

**The coding agent AUDITS the contract against the real baseline + evaluator code and PROPOSES any
additional sections it finds necessary** (as options for human sign-off, not silent additions).
The two gaps above are the floor, not the ceiling.

### M3 — One contract text, injected into EVERY operation
The extended contract is written once and injected into **all operator prompts** — improve,
combine, repair, novelty, and the new init-generation prompt — matching the existing shared-injection
pattern. No per-operator copies, no drift. improve/combine violate it least (they copy working
parents), but uniform injection costs nothing and immediately patches novelty's crash rate
(currently the cap on the grace period's value).

### M4 — Init lineages get grace-period protection
All init lineages are protected (the `select_parent` condition broadens from "novelty lineage in
window" to "novelty OR init lineage in window"). No special-casing any init candidate — a baseline
on the frontier gets a no-op from protection (max-weight rule caps overlap).

### M5 — No privileged init candidate; two run modes
There is NO structurally privileged "incumbent." Two supported modes:
- **generated-only:** all N init candidates generated from the contract (the pure cold-start case — new
  problems with no baseline). Accepted cost: the early frontier is entirely first-drafts; more
  budget spent climbing to competence. That is the price of genericity.
- **generated + supplied:** user supplies a baseline (e.g. this problem's hand-tuned tree) via
  `--baseline`, entering as one more init candidate with **zero special treatment** beyond
  existing in the starting set.
Reporting comparisons against a supplied reference are report-time choices, not search
architecture.

### M6 — Init-generation prompt exposure: contract + architecture-free skeleton (bare minimum)
The init-generation prompt exposes the contract (M2) plus a **minimal skeleton in pseudocode/English** —
the *shape* of a valid candidate (load data per contract → build model → train → save per
convention) with no real model code. Rationale: (1) on a new problem there IS no real example to
show, so the prompt cannot structurally depend on one — the skeleton is derivable from the
contract alone; (2) on this problem it avoids tree re-anchoring entirely. Bare-minimum exposure,
architecture-free. (Rejected: injecting the tree baseline's real code as a worked example — anchors,
and doesn't generalize to baseline-less problems.)

### M7 — CLI: orthogonal flags, no hidden implications
- `--gen-inits N` — number of init candidates to generate (default 2–3 range; 0 = none). Each is a paid
  LLM call before the run proper.
- `--baseline PATH` — the supplied reference model (rename of the existing `--baseline-py`:
  suffix dropped, concept kept). Enters the run as one init candidate with zero search
  privilege. Single path; one baseline per run.
- Run modes are flag combinations: generated-only = `--gen-inits N` + no supplied init candidate;
  generated+supplied = both; today's behavior = supplied only. `--gen-inits` does NOT implicitly
  disregard a supplied init candidate (rejected: overloading one flag with two decisions).

### M8 — Init provenance: differentiated
Generated init candidates mint `init_gen_*` lineage ids; the supplied baseline mints `init_baseline` (or equivalent).
The report reads differently for "your baseline fell short" vs "our generated attempt
fell short," so provenance distinguishes them. `origin` = "init" family either way.

### M9 — Init-candidate failure policy: repair-in-run for evaluable failures; retry-then-skip for
generation failures
- **Generated init candidate that evaluates and fails** (crash at train/eval): NO special handling — it
  lands as a tagged dead-end, is a protected init lineage (M4), and the existing `repair`
  operator gives it repair attempts via the normal waterfall. Init candidates aren't special; existing
  machinery (repair + grace period) does its job.
- **Generation-time failure** (the init-generation LLM call returns something unusable — no candidate
  file exists to enter the run): one retry, then skip with a loud log; the run proceeds with
  N−1 init candidates. This sliver can't reach the in-run machinery, so it's the only place new handling
  exists.
- **[SCOUT note]** confirm a dead init candidate at try ~0 remains visible to `repair`'s recent-failures
  window long enough to get its shots; if not, consider a slight repair bias toward
  protected-lineage failures (decide at recipe time, not now).

